events.name: I/O Extended 2018 MANAMA (FLUTTER)
events.description:
Flutter is Google's mobile SDK for crafting high-quality native interfaces on iOS and Android in record time. Flutter works with existing code, is used by developers and organizations around the world, and is free and open source.

In our Google IO Extended Flutter codelab, you'll create a simple Flutter app. If you are familiar with object-oriented code and basic programming concepts such as variables, loops, and conditionals, you can complete this codelab. You don't need previous experience with Dart or mobile programming.

A Charged Laptop

events.name: Self-Driving Cars! With Computer Vision and AI

venue.name: Brinc Batelco IoT Hub, Batelco Building

events.description:
Abstract:
Self-driving car is a vehicle that is capable of sensing its environment and navigating without human input. Autonomous cars combine a variety of techniques to perceive their surroundings, including radar, laser light, GPS and computer vision. In this Workshop we will focus on Computer vision. Which is a subset of AI field that deals with how computers can be made for gaining high-level understanding from digital images or videos. In this workshop the attendees will discover a cutting edge technology that scientist will use it in Self-Driving Car technology.

Language:
Arabic with English support where necessary =)

Vision:
• Apply Machine learning concept in an Fun Application. ➢ Learn The basics for AI and Deep learning.

Output:
• Train and Test an simulation on self driving car using Deep learning and Tensorflow.

Workshop Plan :
10:15 – 10:30: Introduction AI and Machine learning
10:30 – 11:00: Programming language syntax
11:00 – 12:00: Neural Network and CNN
1:00 – 1:30: Self-Driving Car simulation Environment.
1:30 – 2:00: Building the Project

events.name: Building Digital Skills of The Future
events.description:
Join Google Developer Group Manama and its speakers for an interesting informal discussion on what the digital skills of the future are and how to best upskill talent.

Their casual panel represents a range of perspectives across AI, Gaming, Digital Agencies and Data Science, each with their own insights into where the current job trends are heading, what are the recommendations on upskilling and the possible barriers to adoption of those specific technologies. events.name: Unravelling CPUs and writing your first Emulator!
events.description:
Speaker: Ameen Altajer

Abstract:
In this session, we'll go through a fantastic journey to understand how microprocessors are designed and built from the ground up.

We'll start with the history of how the microprocessor became the beast we all know and love today, whether you're an Intel or an AMD fan, it's a must to understand what humans have been through to really appreciate what the transistor has brought to mankind and how it became the most important key in our the digital revolution.

Before we finish, we'll write an emulator to the very basic CHIP8 processor so you can understand how emulators work internally, we'll also see how real emulators (like Nintendo's NES, Sony's PS2 and PS3) work from the inside and we'll look at few good examples of some of the most impressive homebrew CPUs out there.

Join us in an adventure to unravel how computers exactly work, see the magic that powers up your beloved laptop! If you know a bit of programming you'll definitely enjoy this session.

events.name: Women Board Members in Tech [Open to All]
events.description:
Join us in fireside chat for both organizations & MENA women in tech, as we explore: How do we drive greater gender balance on MENA boards in technology companies.

Speakers: Leena Al-Olaimy: Co-Founder of Diversity on Board, Lana Alattar, GDG Manama Lead, WTM Ambassador

Details:
How do we drive greater gender balance on MENA boards in technology companies?

A report by the Hawkamah Institute of Corporate Governance revealed that women in the GCC account for just 1.5 percent of corporate board seats. While, according to the 2020 World Economic Forum’s Global Gender Gap Report, at the current rate of progress, it would take the MENA region 140 years to close the economic gender gap.

At the same time, the market power of increasing women’s participation in the workforce, could add an estimated $2.7 trillion to the Middle East’s economy by 2025. This session will touch upon how we close the gap between the demand and supply of potential female directors in the tech industry, to accelerate our social and economic progress.

For MENA organizations in Tech: This session will offer some strategic recommendations for overcoming the challenges that large and small tech companies face in diversifying their boards, how to build high performing diverse boards, and how that can correlate with positive business results.

For MENA women in Tech: This session will offer recommendations on how to become a board member—including how to get your first board position—and preparing for board directorship.
